:::summary
Medieval Europe — roughly the thousand years between the fall of Rome (476 AD) and the beginning of the Renaissance (c. 1400) — was not the "Dark Ages" of secular myth but the age in which Christianity transformed the ruins of Rome into the civilization of Christendom: building the great cathedrals, founding the universities, synthesizing classical philosophy with Christian theology, and establishing the legal, political, and cultural foundations on which the modern West stands. Understanding medieval Europe is essential to understanding everything that came after it.
:::

